Czech discovery: a substance that operates on the HIV virus ""
A team of Czech and German new combinations that can slow the spread of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the substance is that it is also on the virus that have already developed an immunity to the drugs..
is, in some cases, the upper hand on the fact that the combination is not as on the common variants of the virus as well as some drugs already available. available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at the present..
can prolong the life of patients through a mixture of drugs that prevent the spread of the HIV virus in the body..
is, however, a series of side effects.
of this is the development of so-called resistant viruses on which the drugs have no effect...
The work of the three institutions, the National Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for a way to cope with the resistance of the virus. the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt..
This combination is blocking the development of the virus in a different way of all drugs used to date and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of researchers leads them to discover new substances "improved", on the basis of their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their routes on the from the virus.
The metalocarboranes have a single three-dimensional structure: two cages to multiple walls are formed by the atoms of, hydrogen and carbon and connected by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt..
A traitor and.
The HIV is a protein of the HIV virus which is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease there would be no birth of infectious particles of the virus.
If you stop the HIV protease, it will stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body of the patient, the researchers explained in a press release issued by the Institute of organic chemistry and biochemistry at of the National Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In their work published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic link, which is then systematically amended..
A little but more reliable..
The effectiveness of this series of substances on the HIV has been tested in test tubes and its variants, obtained from patients infected with HIV..
On the current version of the enzyme, the effect of metalocarboranes is not as strong as on the clinical medicine, however it is not on the resistant against which the current drugs are often ineffective.
The metalocarboranes, with their unique mechanism of action and their other properties as their biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical changes are therefore interesting to consider more to move towards the development of effective drugs against HIV, "says Pavlína Řezáčová, director of the structural biology laboratory of the Institute of organic chemistry and biochemistry and molecular genetics Institute of the National Academy of Sciences. of Sciences.
