Islam can be French?
and pragmatism in a secular state.
Roger Bootle, Deloitte
Some readers will be lured by this new book, fans of the author's latest book, "Why the French do not like the headscarf" (2006), an elegant and well documented on an issue that has divided and concerned the country for the past 15 years and whose effects are still being felt today..
The last book by Mr. Bowen presents a much broader and more ambitious..
anthropologist, it does not only want to know what the politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is happening in the country..
He spent many months in mosques, schools and institutes that now in France this queM. Bozen called "" for the 5m-6m Muslims.
He knows very well listen and reproduce the debates between teachers and students on the issues that concern them most.
A Muslim must marry in a mosque or at the town hall (or both)?
The evolution and the rights of homosexuals should be taught to young Muslims?
A Muslim woman can marry a non-Muslim?
A Muslim can use a banking system based on the interests to obtain a loan?
These are practical problems, he says, which are the daily lot, rather than the political dramas that concern to the media.
The author identifies a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, all unknown to the general public, except perhaps Tariq Ramadan, a Muslim Arab born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how to be both a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They do not push the debate until the end.
Lesconservateurs do not believe in the idea of a French or European Islam.
intellectuals and activists who have been interviewed by Mr. Bowen are generally in agreement with their counterparts lawyers of a Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia that today, are a small part of Muslims in Europe..
M Bowen believes that the values of Muslims and the secular nature of the French could be compatible..
But a compromise can be achieved only with the efforts of each camp.
He wondered how the French politicians (and the intellectual elite if virulent of secularism) are really committed to pluralism.
According to him, Muslims have not been spoiled, compared to Catholics, Protestants and Jews who have also had to make compromises with the secular republicanism.
Rather than a growing pragmatism, he detects a "of key values".
Islam can be French? After reading this book, one is tempted to say "yes, but not yet."
