In China, a change of direction
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by the propaganda poster, "The Mother Earth is too tired to accommodate more children" and "A baby, it is a more".
have learned the lesson that the authorities of the Government of Shanghai, alarmed by the lack of birth rate of their city and the ageing of the population, have radically changed direction this summer and began to encourage young couples to have more than one child; their response has been instantaneous and firm:..
We have already given all our time and energy to one child.
There is no second, said Wang, 31, Director of Human Resources and who has a son of 8 months.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, creating two generations of children with good cheeks and spoiled, dubbed the "little emperors", a crisis of the population threatens the country..
According to the United Nations, the average birth rate fell from 1.8 children per couple, compared to six when the policy was implemented.
The distribution of the population, while it is expected that the number of residents aged 60 and over will explode, 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050. This figure is well above the overall average of about 20 percent.
This imbalance is even worse in the rich coastal cities with a highly educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over accounted for nearly 22 percent of the population of residents in Shanghai, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning Commission (Commission of the Shanghai Municipal and) said that the fertile couples to have babies in order "to help reduce the proportion of the ageing population and to prevent a lack of manpower in the future."..
Shanghai is on the verge of becoming "too old - but not as rich, however, that the developed countries such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
A
in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is to this day, without doubt, the most controversial requirement introduced by the Communist government.
who violate this policy may have to pay huge fines - up to three times their annual income - and suffer discrimination in the workplace.
The Chinese authorities have attributed to the police on duty to help the country to avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while the lawyers for human rights have denounced abuses in the implementation of this policy.
In rural areas, some representatives of the authority have forced women pregnant with a second child to have abortions.
In addition, many couples have used to selective abortions leading to a ratio of boys girls abnormally high..
In recent years, the authorities of the population have gradually softened their position on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they have been more exceptions to the rule - including for residents of cities, members of ethnic minorities and the cases in which the man and woman are already - and in 2007, they have softened much of their slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research (Institute of Population Research), at Peking University, said that the authorities of the central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one partner is an only child.
In July, Shanghai has become the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, the posters encouraging families to have only one child have been replaced by copies of regulations who has the right to have a second child and how to apply for..
The city government has dispatched family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples, at their home, and under their door..
He has also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child.
According to the head of family planning, the response has been disappointing.
response
officials in a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in requests for records of couples wanting a second child after the launch of the campaign, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of, for example, is still only four to five requests per month.
in Shanghai, disappointed, said that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city, in 2010, is still expected to be only about 165 000 - slightly higher than in 2009 but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, Head of the Family Planning Committee of family planning in the municipality of Caolu of Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to fill their first child, she said.
Yang, 27 years and his wife, Liu, 26 years, said they would love to have two children and that they are legally allowed..
But like many Chinese, they have only the minimum health insurance and life assurance given by the government.
Without a social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
The mistakenly see that the one-child policy is a problem of rights, "said Yang, a construction engineer, whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child.
It is true, we are the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not only the law.
It is money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation.
Wang, of Human Resources, said she wanted only a single child because she was itself. "We were at the centre of the family and had used that everyone cares." ""
We do not have the habit of taking care of someone else, and we really do not want to take care of others. ""
Chen Zijian, 42 years and owner of a translation company puts it more bluntly.
For couples working at two, middle class, which the birth rate, he says, he must be selfish pourbien succeed.
of 20 or 30 years have grown up seeing their parents struggle in the early days of the capitalist and do not want to have themselves this way of life, "he says.
Even one child a lot of time with his parents, "he says..
A mother must abandon at least two years of her social life.
there are the problems of space - "You you must change your apartment" - and planning - "When your child has only 9 months, you need to write his CV for a place in the best mother tongue." "
Most of his friends are willing to this experience once again, said Chen, but not both..
Our generation is the first to benefit from a higher standard of living, "he says.
We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
The Group of the United Nations has plans for the reduction of emissions emissions
The climate conference, sponsored by the United Nations characterized by and mutual recriminations - is back in under the spotlight Friday, due to the publication of a document outlining the ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations supporting most of the burden in the coming years time.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, said the remaining obstacles, as it has informed the path to take..
But it was seen as an important step forward in the negotiations that are short of time, with more than 100 world leaders from arriving next week in Copenhagen.
by a special working group of the United Nations, the text does not say how many rich countries would give to the poor to cope with global warming, short and long term...
And it offers a wide range of options for the key issues, including how the developed economies and the emerging economies could reduce their production of carbon and what would be the upper limit of the increase in global temperature increase that those responsible would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility in the process, said John Coequyt, Representative àWashington of the Sierra Club..
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who has written six pages of the document, has studied a text of 180 pages to focus on what was described by the Secretary-General on the United Nations climate change, Yvo de Boer, as "the full picture."..
It shows the guidelines of a possible agreement in which the industrial nations reduce their emissions in 2020, from 25 to 45 percent compared to 1990 levels, while the major developing countries, during the same period, reduced by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union has also relaunched the negotiations, Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change - to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercation occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, US Representative of the United States to the negotiating climate has rejected any discussion the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, in comparison with the voluntary efforts made by the major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed countries. developed countries..
This change is the signal that the Obama administration is becoming harder to China that the Bush administration has been, it was two years ago...
The United States will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions of the major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text does not enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Vice Minister of Foreign Affairs, He Yafei has said that the chief negotiator, "common sense", was "extremely irresponsible" for having said earlier in the week that the United States would not financially China to combat global warming..
With the future economic trajectories of the world's major powers involved, defects both within the and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more concerned with the rescue of individual economies that the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States querellant on their respective obligations while poorer nations insist on the fact that the two dozen countries the most influential countries ignore scientific imperatives to act more boldly..
Ricardo ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of the reduction of greenhouse gases, even if the vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in their attempt to make the major emitters accountable for their actions.
It really is a game in which has developed a new economic hegemony, said ulate, who is also on the climate for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they would continue to put pressure for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the major participants say that the negotiations will lead to a minimum, a political agreement..
The Alliance of Small Island States which brings together 43 members, has drafted a proposal for a Treaty of 24 pages, early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the unit of the European Commission, said that the action of small island states has "put political pressure on the political process is complete,", in part by what they are now and they emerging economies such as China and India, to act....
The debates have become a matter of urgency, while delegates focused on the fact that they should solve most of the problems pending before the heads of governments come to an agreement.
officials such as the Indian Minister of the environment minister, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese are descended from their plane and rushed into the building of the Bella Center to attend meetings in camera and conferences of information, in order to make claims that will be considered during the following week.
The real image of the -- in which people and out of the Palais des each day activists guitar players are mocking countries which they will and that proposals are and distributed on paper rather than by - is a real challenge real.
The intensity is: almost all key ministers are here and not later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the big boys, "said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy of Conservation International.
