The Turkish dissolved the pro-Kurdish party, decision
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled Friday the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party in the country, a decision which was immediately followed by expressions of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul..
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which is to reach out to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict..
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) has been dissolved because it had become a "home of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," said to the press, the President of the Hasim, at the end of four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously of the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to the dissolution, said Mr Kiliç said, adding that 37 of party officials, including its President Ahmet Türk and Aysel Tugluk, are banned from politics for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Tugluk and the confiscation of the property of the party..
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that would leave Parliament rather than sit as without label.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accused the DTP to obey the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organisation by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal policy of the PKK rebels.
The party, however, that there was "no organic links" with the PKK but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with him.
The verdict of the Court comes at a time when the government is to reach out to the Kurdish community in proposing a series of measures strengthening its rights, to try to the support of to the PKK and put an end to the conflict.
The leaders of the DTP had said that a dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in the southeast Anatolia, where many demonstrations against the conditions of detention of the PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
the announcement of justice, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP in Diyarbakir, the largest city in the majority of Kurds..
The security forces fired tear gas and used water cannons, while protesters were throwing Molotov cocktails and stones, with.
people also in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said that the decision of Justice would "deepen the despair.".
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (,) by banning a party, "he said to the press..
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of the parties.
does not, "said Minister of Energy Taner Yildiz..
This decision is a total of democratic openness launched by the government, "commented on the political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, "he added.
On Thursday, the PKK has claimed an attack that had killed seven soldiers three days earlier in the northern Turkey, one of the most deadly in recent months.
