emergency braking is now mandatory
As has occurred with the ABS anti-lock system and as it will take place with the ESP stability control systems, to emergency will be a compulsory element on European cars....
They are already mandatory on passenger cars and light commercial vehicles registered, while for the rest of the vehicles a waiting period was set up at the end of February 2011..
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, even if, by its mode of action, it can also help to prevent many rear shocks.
The assistant emergency braking is increasing the pressure on the brakes in an emergency cases detected by the system through the kick given by the driver..
But it does not always maintained the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the manufacturer of components for cars Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to build on the brakes before the collision, and half of them had not taken advantage of its strength.
Up to 1 100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in revancha, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance that the car needs to stop. stop.
According to a study of the EU, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1 100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularization of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: It calculates that a disaster on four, with casualties would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system which, thanks to a radar or a camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to act on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it increasing the pressure on the pedal, if this is necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device is the maximum effort on the brakes in order to minimize the damage.
